You can also write your function directly inside the apply call. I like to use sapply, although I know some will ding me for not using a class perfect return function from purrr.

#R 

As a function instead of a for loop. 

count_to_N <- function(N = 20){ 
#' This functions takes a numeric input N 
#' and prints 1:N to the console 

if( is.numeric(N) == FALSE ) { 
stop("N should be a number")
   } else if ( N < 1 ) { 
message("counting backwards!") 
}   

rng = 1 : floor(N) # ignore decimals 
print( rng )

}

count_to_N()

sapply (dataframe, 
function(x){
   mean( is.na(x) )
   }
) 

is more easily interpretable in my opinion. You can always create a function directly wherever one is meant to be called.

A good example in why you use one or the other would be in identifying the proportion of NAs in each row or column of data. That is an apply() situtation.¬†

apply(X = iris, MARGIN = 2, FUN = function(x){mean(is.na(x))})¬† # 2 for columns, 1 for rows.¬†
¬†# returns a NAMED numeric.¬† 616 bytes¬†

do.call would be much weirder to write, returns an unnamed numeric list, 96 bytes.¬†do.call( what = function(x){ 
    r = NULL 
    for(i in 1:ncol(x)){ 
        r = c(r, mean(is.na( x[,i] ))) 
    }
    return(r)

}, args = list(iris)¬†)

The do.call method takes marginally longer in this instance as well.

